estimated-input-latency.name: estimated-input-latency
estimated-input-latency.helpText: Primarily a measure of the main thread's activity. There is a 90% probabililty a user would encounter input latency of this amount or less. 10% of touches can expect additional latency.

aria-valid-attr.description: Element aria-* attributes are valid ARIA attributes

color-contrast.description: Background and foreground colors have a sufficient contrast ratio

image-alt.name: image-alt
image-alt.description: Every image element has an alt attribute

label.description: Every form element has a label

tabindex.description: No element has a tabindex attribute greater than 0

content-width.description: Content is sized correctly for the viewport

external-anchors-use-rel-noopener.name: external-anchors-use-rel-noopener
external-anchors-use-rel-noopener.description: Site opens external anchors using rel="noopener".
external-anchors-use-rel-noopener.helpText: Anchors that open in a new tab should use target="_blank" and rel="noopener" so the opening page's performance does not suffer.

appcache-manifest.name: appcache-manifest
appcache-manifest.description: Site does not use Application Cache
appcache-manifest.helpText: Application Cache has been deprecated by Service Workers. Consider implementing an offline solution using the Cache Storage API.

geolocation-on-start.name: geolocation-on-start
geolocation-on-start.description: Page does not automatically request geolocation on page load
geolocation-on-start.helpText: Using the geolocation without context is a poor user experience. Always tie API permissions to user interactions.

link-blocking-first-paint.name: link-blocking-first-paint
link-blocking-first-paint.description: Site does not use <link> that delay first paint
link-blocking-first-paint.helpText: <link> elements are delaying the first paint of your page! For stylesheets, consider inlining or using the disabled and media attributes. For HTML Imports, use the async attribute. These techniques will make the resource(s) non-render blocking.

no-console-time.name: no-console-time
no-console-time.description: Site does not use console.time() in its own scripts
no-console-time.helpText: Consider using the User Timine API (performance.mark() and performance.measure()), which is a standard, uses high resolution timestamps, and has the added benefit of integrating with the DevTools timeline.

no-datenow.name: no-datenow
no-datenow.description: Site does not use Date.now() in its own scripts
no-datenow.helpText: Consider using performance.now(), which has better precision than Date.now() and always increases at a constant rate, independent of the system clock.

no-document-write.name: no-document-write
no-document-write.helpText: Consider using <script async> to load scripts. document.write() is considered harmful for performance.

no-mutation-events.name: no-mutation-events
no-mutation-events.description: Site does not use Mutation Events in its own scripts
no-mutation-events.helpText: Using Mutation events degrades application performance. They are deprecated in the DOM events spec, replaced by MutationObservers.

no-old-flexbox.name: no-old-flexbox
no-old-flexbox.description: Site does not use the old CSS flexbox
no-old-flexbox.helpText: The older spec for CSS Flexbox (display: box) is deprecated and less performant. Consider using the newer version (display: flex), which does not suffer from the same issues.

no-websql.name: no-websql
no-websql.description: Site does not use WebSQL DB.
no-websql.helpText: Web SQL Database is deprecated. Consider implementing an offline solution using IndexedDB.

uses-http2.displayValue: 5 resources were not served over h2
uses-http2.name: uses-http2
uses-http2.description: Site uses HTTP/2 for its own resources
uses-http2.helpText: h2 offers many benefits over its http/1.1 predecessor: binary, multiplexing, server push, etc. See this FAQ for more information.

uses-passive-event-listeners.name: uses-passive-event-listeners
uses-passive-event-listeners.description: Site uses passive listeners to improve scrolling performance
uses-passive-event-listeners.helpText: Passive event listeners enable better scrolling performance. If you don't call preventDefault() in your wheel,mousewheel,touchstart,touchmove event listeners, make them passive: addEventListener('touchstart', ..., {passive: true}).

aggregations.name: Progressive Web App
aggregations.description: These audits validate the aspects of a Progressive Web App.

score.name: App can load on offline/flaky connections
score.description: Ensuring your web app can respond when the network connection is unavailable or flaky is critical to providing your users a good experience. This is achieved through use of a Service Worker.

score.name: Page load performance is fast
score.description: Users notice if sites and apps don't perform well. These top-level metrics capture the most important perceived performance concerns.

subItems.name: coming-soon
subItems.description: Touch input gets a response in < 150ms

subItems.name: coming-soon
subItems.description: App is interactive without jank after the first meaningful paint

score.name: Site is progressively enhanced
score.description: Progressive enhancement means that everyone can access the basic content and functionality of a page in any browser, and those without certain browser features may receive a reduced but still functional experience.

score.name: Network connection is secure
score.description: Security is an important part of the web for both developers and users. Moving forward, Transport Layer Security (TLS) support will be required for many APIs.

score.name: User can be prompted to Add to Homescreen
score.description: While users can manually add your site to their homescreen in the browser menu, the prompt (aka app install banner) will proactively prompt the user to install the app if the below requirements are met and the user has visited your site at least twice (with at least five minutes between visits).

score.name: Installed web app will launch with custom splash screen
score.description: A default splash screen will be constructed, but meeting these requirements guarantee a high-quality and customizable splash screen the user sees between tapping the home screen icon and your app’s first paint.

score.name: Address bar matches brand colors
score.description: The browser address bar can be themed to match your site. A theme-color meta tag will upgrade the address bar when a user browses the site, and the manifest theme-color will apply the same theme site-wide once it's been added to homescreen.

score.name: Design is mobile-friendly
score.description: Users increasingly experience your app on mobile devices, so it's important to ensure that the experience can adapt to smaller screens.

aggregations.name: Best Practices
aggregations.description: We've compiled some recommendations for modernizing your web app and avoiding performance pitfalls. These audits do not affect your score but are worth a look.

score.name: Avoiding APIs that harm the user experience

subItems.name: coming-soon
subItems.description: Service worker makes use of push notifications, if appropriate

subItems.name: coming-soon
subItems.description: Tap targets are appropriately sized for touch

subItems.name: coming-soon
subItems.description: Payment forms marked up with [autocomplete] attributes

subItems.name: coming-soon
subItems.description: Login forms marked up with [autocomplete] attributes

subItems.name: coming-soon
subItems.description: Input fields use appropriate [type] attributes for custom keyboards
